BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:oLpFfGwXFuSS7Bcd_P5wT
SUMMARY:SAM Body + Mind: Activity Days
DTSTAMP:20260317T051039Z
DTSTART:20260321T160000Z
DESCRIPTION:Experience a full spectrum of grounding\, creative\, and wellne
	ss-focused practices with SAM Body \\+ Mind: Activity Days. Designed to re
	juvenate both inner and outer worlds\, each session offers a mix of mindfu
	l movement\, quiet reflection\, hands-on creativity\, and holistic care. P
	articipate in gentle Qigong to awaken your energy\, enjoy replenishing mom
	ents with acupuncture\, or settle into the calm of silent reading in a pea
	ceful shared space. Explore your artistic side with natural dye and art-ma
	king workshops that nourish connections to yourself and the natural world.
	 Come for one activity or stay for the full experience-each offering invit
	es you to slow down\, reconnect\, and care for your body and mind. 8:30 am
	 | Doors open 9-10 am | Tai Chi/Qigong With Sensei Jody Garcia 10 am-1 pm 
	| Workshops Art workshop with NW Expressive and Creative Arts Institute Na
	tural dyes workshop with Earth Corps Acupuncture with Dr. Yanzi Jiang\, Dr
	. Milo Jackson\, and Dr. Nikeeta Shah noon-2 pm | Musical performance Ambi
	ent Vinyl DJ set performed by DJ Raica 1-2 pm | Silent reading With West S
	eattle Book Club Food and drinks Food and beverages will be available for 
	purchase from Shooby Doo Catering in the PACCAR Pavilion. Presenting Spons
	or\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/sam-body-mind-activity
	-days/17592413/2026-03-21T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/sam-body-mind-activity-da
	ys/17592413/2026-03-21T00
LOCATION:Olympic Sculpture Park\, 2901 Western Ave\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT5H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:GfPdPocxZBwpmg52J-Pzc
SUMMARY:Alaska Cruise & Travel Show
DTSTAMP:20260317T051039Z
DTSTART:20260321T160000Z
DESCRIPTION:Event Overview Join us in Seattle for the Alaska Cruise & Trave
	l Show and begin planning your voyage to one of the world's most extraordi
	nary destinations. This immersive event brings together travel inspiration
	\, cultural experiences\, and exclusive cruise offers all in one place. Ex
	perience live music and theater presentations that celebrate Alaska's land
	scapes and heritage. Participate in hands-on activities including gold pan
	ning and axe throwing and meet with cruise specialists to explore itinerar
	ies and take advantage of limited-time booking offers. Attendees may enter
	 for the chance to win one Alaska cruise for two and one of six $500 Holla
	nd America Line gift cards. Admission is free. Reserve your place at www.a
	laskatravelshow.com.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/alas
	ka-cruise-travel-show/18224461/2026-03-21T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Cul
	ture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/alaska-cruise-travel-show
	/18224461/2026-03-21T00
LOCATION:Bell Harbor International Conference Center\, 2211 Alaskan Way\, S
	eattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:HGaoTuEoppGjXvAiPiyzj
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260317T051039Z
DTSTART:20260321T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-03-21T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-03-21T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:4db2oWUglYWsmDUpre5cL
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260317T051039Z
DTSTART:20260321T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-21T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-21T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
